title: Beauchamp Tower
description: The Beauchamp Tower (Pronounced "Beecham") was one of the towers used for keeping prisoners, including the future Queen Elizabeth I. This was built by Edward I in 1281 when it replaced a fortified gatehouse that stood on this site. The tower was said to be named after Thomas Beauchamp, Earl of Warwick, who was a prisoner here between 1397 and 1399. Also known as Cobham's Tower after Henry Brooke, Lord Cobham, who died here after 14 years of imprisonment.

title: The Scotch Malt Whisky Society
description:
The Scotch Malt Whisky Society, where members around the world unite in their enjoyment of exceptional single cask, single malt whisky.

Capturing rarity and perfection in a glass, the Society's malt whisky attracts curious and discerning whisky lovers from all corners of the globe.
Only ever bottled from a single cask, selected from a range of over 120 whisky distilleries every Society whisky bottling is exceptional.

Visit us and discover why the Society is the world's premier destination for the true malt whisky lover.

Since 1983 the Society has offered a unique range of single cask single malt whisky to it's members across the Globe. In the UK there are two other Venues are in Edinburgh, plus rooms in Asia and Europe.

The London Members Room of the Scotch Malt Whisky Society on 19 Greville Street, London, EC1N 8SQ.
